## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of history in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
History is the bounded retention and reference structure
that preserves meaningful past states,
past events,
past relations,
and past outcomes
without collapsing them into current truth.

History is not merely old data storage.
It is the semantic layer that makes pastness,
sequence,
change,
and reconstruction meaningful.

## architectural_position
History sits between:
- prior events and states
- current reference needs
- audit/reconstruction needs
- replay/reference boundaries
- narrative and record continuity

## required_behavior
- historical identity must remain explicit
- current and historical meanings must remain distinct
- sequence and causality must remain reviewable
- reconstruction must remain bounded
- historical reference must not overwrite current truth

## canonical_rules
- history must not masquerade as current state
- historical reconstruction must preserve uncertainty where needed
- replay/reference must remain distinguishable from original occurrence
- destructive overwrite of prior trace is prohibited
- ambiguous historical interpretation fails closed

## state_model
The history domain distinguishes:
- retained history
- reference history
- reconstructed history
- restricted history
- archived history

## actor_boundary
- recorder
- reference actor
- reviewer
- operator
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if historical basis is missing, stop reconstruction
- if current and historical are mixed, fail closed
- if replay/reference mode is unclear, route to review
- if history is archived, preserve bounded read-only trace

## review_checklist
- current/historical separation is explicit
- reconstruction boundary is explicit
- replay/reference distinction is explicit
- retention intent is explicit
